  <article class="container-narrow py-10 prose-tool">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">About the Reviewers</h1>
    <p class="lead text-lg text-slate-700">
      Kefiw uses role-based human review so users can see who is responsible for the math, the evidence framing, and the safety wording.
    </p>

    <TrustNav current="/about-the-reviewers/" />

    <h2>Why this exists</h2>
    <p>
      Most tool sites say a page is &ldquo;reviewed&rdquo; without saying what that means. Kefiw does the opposite. The review label tells you whether a page was checked for implementation accuracy, evidence framing, health-safety wording, contractor scope, real-estate workflow, or some combination of those. That matters because a word-game helper, a roof estimate, a seller proceeds calculator, and a health-routing page do not carry the same risk.
    </p>

    <h2>The review roles</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong><a href="/engineering-review/">Engineering review</a></strong> covers formulas, calculations, input handling, browser behavior, unit conversions, and implementation correctness. Engaged on every page.</li>
      <li><strong><a href="/scientific-review/">Scientific review</a></strong> covers source quality, evidence framing, assumptions, uncertainty, and clear explanation of limits. Engaged on every page.</li>
      <li><strong><a href="/registered-nurse-review/">Registered nurse review</a></strong> covers health and care safety wording, escalation language, red-flag copy, and non-diagnosis boundaries. Engaged on health pages, Care pages, senior-care planning, and wellbeing Tracks.</li>
      <li><strong><a href="/remodeling-contractor-review/">Remodeling contractor review</a></strong> covers Property Improve pages where scope, materials, labor assumptions, bid language, and quote-risk questions matter.</li>
      <li><strong><a href="/realtor-review/">Realtor review</a></strong> covers Property pages where seller proceeds, buyer cash-to-close, commission, closing costs, ownership, and real-estate workflow assumptions matter.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How the roles work together</h2>
    <p>
      The same page can carry more than one review role. A roof Track is engineered for deterministic math, scientifically reviewed for uncertainty language, and approved by contractor review for scope and quote questions. A seller proceeds Track is engineered for the calculation, scientifically reviewed for assumptions, and approved by realtor review for workflow framing. Health and care pages add RN approval for safety wording.
    </p>

    <h2>What users are usually trying to do</h2>
    <p>
      People rarely come to Kefiw looking for abstract definitions. They are usually trying to solve a puzzle, write a line that sounds right, check a formula, compare two options, or understand whether a tool result is safe to rely on. The review system exists to make those tasks clearer and less misleading.
    </p>

    <h2>What a review label does not mean</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>It does not mean a page is personalized to your situation.</li>
      <li>It does not mean a tool replaces a clinician, lawyer, accountant, financial adviser, or any other licensed professional.</li>
      <li>It does not mean a single reviewer approves every sentence on the site for every possible use case.</li>
      <li>It does mean the page has an identified staff approval scope, which is documented in plain language and linked from the page.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Read the details</h2>
